`crates/ctx-core/src` is the shared-definitions crate that every other CTX tool (ctx-scan, ctx-context, ctx-brief, ctx-status) depends on to avoid re-implementing security-sensitive or format-sensitive logic. Depending on this crate buys you: the canonical secret/binary denylist, the canonical hash-sidecar schema, and the canonical STATUS.md table parser/escaper — all pure, dependency-free modules with no I/O or crate-specific error types.

The three modules are independent (no cross-file coupling within this dir) but each anchors a cross-crate contract: `access` must stay the sole denylist source (ADR-023) since a divergent copy in a consumer crate is a secret-exfiltration risk; `hashtree`'s `DirNode`/`hex_hash` must be produced and parsed identically by ctx-scan (writer) and ctx-context (reader), including the `f:`/`d:` child-key prefix convention; `status_table`'s escape/parse pair must round-trip exactly so ctx-brief and ctx-status agree on table contents. In all three, consumers map the neutral outputs (bools, `Option<&str>`, `Row`/`DirNode` structs) into their own typed errors rather than copying logic — this crate never defines a crate-specific error type itself.

`lib.rs` just re-exports the three modules; there's no additional glue logic to track. A typical cross-crate change starts by editing the relevant module here, then updating every dependent crate's call site — never by duplicating the logic downstream.